\begin_layout Section
Coin Collector
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
By pressing the 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

Next
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 button in the lower right corner while the Coin Collector mode is selected
 in the view pager, assuming the GPS is working and the headphones are plugged
 in.
 If GPS-connection or headphones are missing a pop up is showed telling
 what is missing.
 To be able to use the application in a proper way a GPS-connection and
 headphones has to be used.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
When Coin Collector is launched, a route of coins is generated based on
 the values set in the settings view.
 The coins are generated in a circle from you, all being within the reachable
 and by integration with Google maps the coins is going to be located on
 reachable location such as roads and trails.
 To start the run the 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

play-button
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 in the lower right corner of 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "fig:Coin collector"

\end_inset

 is pressed.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Pressing the play button in the lower-, the user will start hearing a repeating
 sound --- hereafter referred to as the navigation sound (see chapter 3.1).
 However, in order for the navigation sound to be heard from the correct
 direction, the GPS has to calculate the direction of which the user is
 heading.
 At present, the user has to move approximately 10 meters for this to be
 done correctly.
 Once the the calculations are done, the user is supposed to run in the
 direction of the sound in order to reach the first coin.
 Apart from the time between each repetition of the navigation sound being
 decreased, a voice feedback is implemented.
 Each hundred meters it tells the user the distance to the coin.
 For example, if the user just passes 200 meters until he reach the coin
 a voice saying 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

200 meters
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 is played.
 When the user passes a hundred meter border the playback speed is restored
 to a slow speed again.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
As the user moves, the navigation sound is being modulated (or completely
 exchanged), as a result of the angular offset mentioned in chapter 3.
 Whenever a user reaches a coin, a synthesized voice informs them that the
 coin has been reached.
 If it's not the last coin, the same voice will let the user know that another
 one has been generated.
 Because of the last coin always being generated at the starting point (see
 chapter 3.3), a finished run should result in the user being back to where
 they started.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The run can be paused at any time by pressing the pause button located at
 the bottom-right, taking the place of the play button while running.
 Pausing the run will stop the navigation sound from repeating and the GPS
 from tracking the user's location.
 To resume from a paused state, the user simply presses the same button
 once again.
 If the user wishes to quit the run completely, they can do so by pressing
 the stop button located at the bottom (VI MASTE HA BILD).
 It's possible to display more information about the current run, either
 by pressing the tabs located at the top or by sweeping horizontally in
 the desired direction.
 The first image in 
